Mono-Hy D2 produced significantly higher yields, sucrose per- centage, and recoverable sugar and extractable sugar per ton than other varieties. ## Brei Nitrate Rating A study of the relationship between the nitrate content of sugarbeet brei and sucrose percentage was initiated in 1972 and is continuing on a much larger scale in 1973. The objective of this program is to use the relationship between nitrate rating (nitrate content of brei), yield and sucrose content to make the grower more aware of his past fertilizer management program. High nitrate contents in brei samples indicate excessive nitrogen levels in the soil. The data in Figure 1 show that as the nitrate rating increases, the sucrose percentage decreases at a rate of approximately 0.77% for every nitrate rating. The Lovell, Goodland, Longmont, Sterling and Gering factory tare labs have been performing nitrate ratings on brei samples this fall. These results will be available later. The relationship in Figure 1 should be used by the agriculturists to evaluate a grower's fertilizer program and encourage him to reduce nitrogen applications if he had high nitrate ratings and low sucrose percentages. Figure 1. Relationship between brei nitrate rating and sucrose percentage. <::A line chart titled "Relationship between brei nitrate rating and sucrose percentage". The y-axis is labeled "% Sucrose" and ranges from 16.00 to 18.75. The x-axis is labeled "Brei Nitrate Rating" and ranges from 1 to 5. The line graph shows a general decreasing trend in sucrose percentage as the brei nitrate rating increases from 1 to 4, then a slight increase from 4 to 5. Specific points on the line are approximately: - Brei Nitrate Rating 1: 18.75% Sucrose - Brei Nitrate Rating 2: 17.75% Sucrose - Brei Nitrate Rating 3: 16.75% Sucrose - Brei Nitrate Rating 4: 16.25% Sucrose - Brei Nitrate Rating 5: 16.35% Sucrose : chart::> Summary Deep soil probes should be taken from prospective sugarbeet fields to a depth of five feet. From the laboratory results and consideration of past cropping history, a fertilizer recommend- ation can be made that will produce maximum returns. Yield responses to applied nitrogen are generally not obtained if soil NO₃-N levels exceed 100 pounds per acre. Results from Colorado State University show fifty percent of the fields in Colo- rado contain enough residual soil nitrogen to produce a 20 ton per acre sugarbeet crop without the application of additional nitrogen fertilizer. High residual soil NO₃-N levels do not go hand in hand with production of quality sugarbeets. If soil NO₃-N levels are extremely high, the grower should be encouraged to plant the field to another crop. 3 Source: https://www.industrydocuments.ucsf.edu/docs/khnk0226
